page.text: The purpose of this Safety Study is to identify the crash problems, determine possible
countermeasures that may reduce the crash frequency and congestion as it relates to
signal visibility, lack of left-turn lanes, and signal timing along the section study area.

The safety study of the SR-91 (Som Center Road) section extends from reference
marker 12.86 to reference marker 13.29 (Stone Creek Drive/Hidden Woods Trail to
Wilson Mills Road) with a total length of 0.43 miles and is identified as number 146 of
the year 2009 Highway Safety Program (HSP). The segment is located in the Village of
SR-91 is a north-south principal arterial, which intersects Wilson Mills Road on the north
end of the corridor study. Wilson Mills Road is an east-west minor arterial west of SR-
91 and a collector east of SR-91. There are two signalized intersections within the
corridor study, which are SR-91 with Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road and Wilson Mills
Road. SR-91 has a 4-lane cross section (two through lanes in each direction) starting
at the southern study limits to just south of the Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road
intersection. From the Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road intersection through the north
end of the study, SR-91 has a 5-lane cross section with dedicated left turn lanes at the
signalized intersection. The posted speed limit along SR-91 is mostly 25 mph with a 35
mph section on the southern end of the study section area.
The predominant crash type in the study area is rear-end crashes with just over 50
percent of the crashes. Sideswipe-passing, left-turn, and angle type crashes account for
the majority of the remaining crashes (14 percent each). The four-lane section of SR-91
south of the Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road intersection had 17 rear-end crashes,
most of which resulted due to vehicles stopped in the inside through lane to make a left-
turn into a driveway. The lack of a two-way left-turn lane on SR-91 within this section is
most likely the contributing factor with these rear-end crashes and possibly poor
pavement friction. The two signalized intersections within the study area had the

SR-91 is a north-south principal arterial, which intersects Wilson Mills Road on the north
end of the corridor study. Wilson Mills Road is an east-west minor arterial, which has
an interchange with I-271 approximately ½ mile west of SR-91. The speed limit on
Wilson Mills Road is 25 MPH within the study area and the speed limit on SR-91 is 35
MPH south of Aintree Park Drive and 25 MPH north of Aintree Park Drive. There are
two signalized intersections within the corridor study, which are shown in Table 1 below.
SR-91 is four lanes (two through lanes in each direction) south of the Aintree Park
drive/Seneca Road intersection and five lanes with dedicated left turn lanes from the
Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road intersection north through the study area. See Figures
1 through 3 for the existing condition diagrams on pages 18 through 20.
The signalized intersection of SR-91 & Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road is an actuated
signal and operates with protected/permissive left-turn phasing on the northbound and
southbound approaches to the intersection (vehicles in left-turn lanes can make a left-
turn on the green arrow or during a green ball after yielding to through traffic). The
traffic signal is a suspended box strain pole design with 12-inch incandescent signal
heads on SR-91 and 8-inch incandescent signal heads for the side streets. There are
pedestrian signal heads and pedestrian pushbuttons for only the east-west crosswalk
on the north side of the intersection; however, there are north-south crosswalks on the
east and west side of the intersection as well.
The signalized intersection of SR-91 & Wilson Mills Road is a fully actuated signal and
operates with protected/permissive left-turn phasing on all four approaches. This signal
is also a suspended box strain pole design with 12-inch incandescent signal heads;
however, the suspended box span is supported by utility poles. There are pedestrian
signal heads for each crosswalk and pedestrian pushbuttons for each crosswalk.
(Crosswalks are on all four legs of the intersection.) This signal is approximately 650
feet from the Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road signal; however, the two signals are not
The condition of the asphalt concrete pavement is in fair condition with some transverse
cracking south of Wilson Mills Road. North of Wilson Mills Road, SR-91 is concrete and
in good condition. In the intersection of SR-91 and Wilson Mills Road and on the
westbound approach to this intersection, the asphalt pavement is in very poor condition,
Poor pavement condition at the intersection of SR-91 & Wilson Mills Road
The pavement markings along SR-91 are in fair condition; however, they should be
remarked within a year or two. At some places, the lane lines are covered up by the
asphalt patching. In addition, the pavement markings at both the Aintree Park
Drive/Seneca Road intersection and Wilson Mills Road intersection need to be
remarked. There is street lighting on utility poles along SR-91 throughout the study
area and at the signalized intersections.
A total of 79 crashes were examined, which occurred between the years of 2007 and
2009 (3 years) within the project limits of SR-91. This resulted in a section crash rate of
8.8 per million vehicles per mile for the section (12.86-13.29). The crash data summary
Figures 4 through 6 show the Collision Diagrams on pages 21 to 23
Crash rate =8.8 crashes per million vehicles per mile
The most predominant crash type is the rear-end crash with 51 percent of all crashes in
the study area. There are several areas where rear-end crashes are occurring. The
four-lane section of SR-91 south of the Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road intersection
had 17 rear-end crashes, most of which resulted due to vehicles stopped in the inside
through lane to make a left-turn into a driveway. The intersection of SR-91 and Aintree
Park Drive/Seneca Road had five northbound rear-end crashes, and the intersection of
SR-91 and Wilson Mills Road had eight northbound rear-end crashes.
Other crash types to note in the study area within the 3-year crash period are
sideswipe-passing crashes with 11, left-turn crashes with 11, and angle crashes with
10. Sideswipe crashes occurred mostly on the approaches to the two signalized
intersections. Of the eleven left-turn crashes, three occurred at the SR-91 and Aintree
Park Drive/Seneca Road intersection, five occurred at the SR-91 and Wilson Mills Road
intersection, and three occurred at the driveway to Pizzazz Pizza just south of Wilson
Mills Road on SR-91. Most of the angle crashes occurred at business drives along SR-
One pedestrian crash occurred in the study area. It involved an eastbound vehicle
making a right-turn to go southbound on SR-91 on a red light and the driver did not see
the pedestrian crossing SR-91. There was also one pedalcycle crash that occurred
along SR-91 at a business drive. The bicyclist was traveling southbound on the
sidewalk and struck a vehicle exiting a business driveway.

A four-hour turning movement count (7-9 AM & 4-6 PM) was completed at SR-91 and
Wilson Mills Road on February 3, 2011. The traffic count is in Appendix B. Based on
the year 2010 ODOT ADT Traffic Survey Reports, the year 2010 ADT along SR-91 is
18,600 (between Mayfield south corp. limit and Wilson Mills Road). Information from
NOACA (regional planning commission) shows that this area is expected to have no
growth rate (or insignificant) in traffic on SR-91 by year 2030.
The signalized intersection of SR-91 and Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road is not
coordinated with any other signal nearby. The northbound and southbound left-turn
phases are lagging at this intersection and occur at the same time if they are activated
in order to avoid the left-turn yellow trap scenario. Cycle lengths at this intersection vary
between 85 and 95 seconds depending on the amount of traffic on the mainline. Traffic
on the side street is consistent with the traffic coming out of Heinen’s Market; however,
there was never a long queue observed on the side street. Traffic on the side street
generally has to wait an average of 30 to 60 seconds to get the green. There are
pedestrian pushbuttons and pedestrian signal heads for the north crosswalk crossing
SR-91. However, these pedestrian pushbuttons are not ADA compliant (see picture
below). There are no pedestrian signal heads to cross Aintree Park Drive or Seneca
Pedestrian pushbutton on northwest corner of SR-91 & Aintree Park Drive
The existing yellow and all-red times are sufficient for the intersection of SR-91 and
Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road (3.6 seconds yellow on mainline and 2.0 seconds all-
red time for each direction). It is recommended to increase the pedestrian flashing
Don’t Walk interval to 17 seconds for the east-west crosswalk. This takes into account
the 3.5 feet per second walking pace, which is in the 2009 MUTCD.
Capacity is the volume of traffic that can pass through a roadway facility in a given
amount of time (vehicles/hour). The concept of Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative
measure of the operation of the traffic flow. LOS considers such factors as speed,
travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, driver inconvenience, safety and
delay. For different transportation facilities, the LOS is based on different measures of
Signalized intersections are measured for average control delay in seconds per vehicle.
Control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay
and final deceleration delay. The delay measurement for vehicles at a signalized
intersection is a combination of driver discomfort, driver frustration and lost travel time.
The LOS rating system as described in the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual gives a
value of A through F to each type of roadway facility representing best to worst traffic
conditions. When designing for roadway improvements, it is desirable to accommodate
design peak hour volumes at a LOS C or D. Table 2 summarizes the levels of service

The signalized intersection of SR-91 & Wilson Mills Road is a fully actuated signal and
operates with protected/permissive left-turn phasing on all four approaches. The
intersection was analyzed in Synchro for the AM and PM peak hours. From the
capacity analysis, the intersection operates at a LOS C during the AM peak hour and at
a LOS D for the PM peak hour. Because this traffic signal is fully actuated, the cycle
lengths will continually vary depending on the demand of traffic at the intersection.
During the AM peak hour, the traffic signal is operating with very little delays with cycle
lengths generally around 80 to 95 seconds. It was observed that the east-west through
phases do not have “dual entry” operation. So if a vehicle is not on the detector loop for
phase 2 (eastbound through phase) and phases 1 and 6 (westbound left-turn and
westbound through) have their green, phase 2 will not get their green unless a vehicle is
on the detector loop. There is nothing wrong with this type of operation; however, if a
vehicle arrives on phase 2 after phases 1 and 6 are on, the vehicle may have to wait
until the following cycle to get the green. To avoid this situation, dual entry should be
When optimizing the signal timings through Synchro, the delay does not change in the
AM peak hour, which means the existing signal timings are optimized. For the PM peak
hour, delays could be reduced if the signal would operate at a shorter cycle length, such
as a 100-second cycle length compared to the average 110 to 130 second cycle length
in the PM peak hour. A shorter cycle length could be accomplished by setting the
maximum greens lower for some or all of the signal phases. In addition, passage/
vehicle extension times could also be adjusted. From the field observations, the
northbound left-turn and eastbound left-turn phases sometimes took quite a while to gap
out. According to the timing sheet, the gap time for these two phases is set at 4.0
seconds. This gap time could be reduced to 3.0 seconds to reduce delays at the

page.text: The yellow and all-red times are sufficient at the Wilson Mills Road intersection (3.6
seconds for yellow and 2.0 seconds of all-red for each phase). However, it is
recommended to increase the Flashing Don’t Walk time from 12 seconds to 18 seconds
on the north crosswalk crossing SR-91 and 21 seconds for the south crosswalk crossing
SR-91. On the north-south crosswalks crossing Wilson Mills Road, it is recommended
to increase the Flashing Don’t Walk times to 21 seconds. These increases are due to
the 3.5 feet per second walking pace, which is in the 2009 MUTCD.
In summary, the traffic signals at SR-91 & Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road and SR-91
& Wilson Mills Road should be coordinated with each other. This could be
accomplished relatively inexpensively by using GPS clocks in each of the controllers for
time based coordination. The controller cabinet at the Wilson Mills Road intersection
may need to be updated in order for coordination to occur. A 90-second cycle length
would work well in the AM peak hours and a 100-second cycle length would work well in
the PM peak hours for coordination of the signals.
Based on field observations and the available crash data, there are several areas that
can be improved within the study area. For the two traffic signals within the study area,
it is recommended to update the existing strain pole design with new mast arms, LED
traffic signal heads and back plates (with 2-inch yellow reflective tape), pedestrian
countdown signals, and update vehicle detection where needed. Most of the pedestrian
pushbuttons at the two signalized intersections are not ADA compliant (they don’t have
the 2-inch pushbutton). See left picture below. Also, since there are two pushbuttons
on the same signal pole, the pushbuttons should be Accessible Pedestrian Signal (APS)
pushbuttons, similar to the one shown below on the right. The pedestrian APS
pushbuttons are recommended to be installed with the new mast arm poles and new
pedestals instead of the existing wood utility poles. By doing so, this would avoid the
use of conduit risers and separate conduits going to each pushbutton making it more

Other recommended improvements to the SR-91 at Wilson Mills Road and the SR-91 at
Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road signalized intersections include installing new signal
control cabinets with GPS clocks so these signals can be coordinated. In addition to the
physical improvements to the two traffic signals in the study area, there are signal timing
recommendations, which are described in the previous section of the report (Section
Nearly half of the rear-end crashes within the section occurred in the 4-lane cross-
section of SR-91 at driveways and/or unsignalized residential streets. Most of these
rear-end crashes occurred due to a vehicle ahead of them was stopped in the through
lane in order to make a left turn into a driveway or side street. The width of pavement in
the 4-lane section is approximately 52 feet from curb to curb, which is the same width of
the 5-lane section just south of the study area and also near the Aintree Park
Drive/Seneca Road intersection. Crash data for years 2007 through 2009 was collected
for the 0.41 mile section just south of this study area in the 5-lane cross section area
(52-feet wide pavement). From this crash data, there were a total of 53 crashes in
which four of these were side-swipe crashes or 7.5 percent of all crashes. Of these four
sideswipe crashes, one occurred on wet pavement. Because there is not a significant
amount of sideswipe crashes in the current 5-lane cross section area, it is reasonable to
assume that by restriping the current 4-lane cross section to five lanes will not increase
the amount of sideswipe crashes and should reduce the amount of rear ends.
Therefore restriping the pavement to two 11-foot lanes and three 10-foot lanes is
recommended; however, because of the longitudinal cracks along the current lane lines,
it is recommended to resurface this 4-lane section by using a 50/50 slag blend before
restriping it to a 5-lane section. In addition, there are two types of drainage catch basins
along the curbs that protrude out into the pavement by one to two feet (see pictures
below). It is recommended to reconstruct these catch basins so the new pavement
does not slope down into the catch basin and there is a smooth ride in case a vehicle
drives near the inlet. It may be possible to plane more than three inches of the asphalt
surface course to avoid reconstructing the catch basins. It seems that the last
resurfacing project did not involve any planing of the older surface course, so the inlets
are lower than what they should be.

There are a number of business driveways along SR-91 between Wilson Mills Road and
Aintree Park Drive/Seneca Road; however, there isn’t a significant amount of driveway

While there are numerous No Parking signs along SR-91, there is only one sign in the
